The goal of this course is to help beginning students develop skills in Yiddish conversation, reading and writing. Yiddish is the medium of a millennium of Jewish life. Students will frequently refer to the history and culture of Ashkenazie Jewry in studying the language. &#8232;&#8232;
Students found this course to be “very fun”, and thoroughly enjoyed use of songs and music to help memorize vocabulary and grammar. A few students found the material to be, at times, “confusing”, and the lessons to be progressing a little too slowly. &#8232;&#8232;
Professor Botwinik is described as a “great instructor”, “one of the most enthusiast professors” students ever had, who was patient and a skilled language teacher.
&#8232;Beginner Yiddish students, including those with limited background in the language, found this course useful, although one student with no prior knowledge of Yiddish found the class quite challenging.
